- Captain Jack Sparrow.

360
00:43:51,970 --> 00:43:54,990
Let's put some distance between us and this island and head out to open sea.

361
00:43:54,990 --> 00:43:59,260
Yes to the first, yes to the second, but only as so far as we keep to the shallows as much as possible.

362
00:43:59,260 --> 00:44:01,550
Now, that seems a bit contradictory, Captain.

363
00:44:01,550 --> 00:44:07,880
I have every faith in your reconciliatory navigational skills, Master Gibbs. Now, where is that monkey? I want to shoot something.

364
00:44:13,410 --> 00:44:13,850
Jack.

365
00:44:13,850 --> 00:44:14,780
Ah.

366
00:44:14,780 --> 00:44:15,730
Elizabeth is in danger.

367
00:44:15,730 --> 00:44:18,560
Have you considered keeping a more watchful eye on her. Maybe just lock her up somewhere?

368
00:44:18,560 --> 00:44:21,200
She is locked up in a prison, bound to hang for helping you.

369
00:44:21,200 --> 00:44:25,450
There comes a time when one must take responsibility for one's mistakes.

370
00:44:27,610 --> 00:44:31,970
I need that compass of yours, Jack. I must trade it for her freedom.

371
00:44:34,720 --> 00:44:35,850
Mr. Gibbs?

372
00:44:35,850 --> 00:44:37,590
Captain?

373
00:44:37,590 --> 00:44:40,480
We have a need to travel upriver.

374
00:44:40,480 --> 00:44:47,690
By need, do you, mean a trifling need, fleeting, as in, say, a passing fancy?

375
00:44:47,690 --> 00:44:51,920
No, a resolute and unyielding need.

376
00:44:51,920 --> 00:44:55,660
What we need to do is make sail for Port Royal with all haste.

377
00:44:55,660 --> 00:45:01,780
William... I shall trade you the compass, if you will help me...

378
00:45:01,780 --> 00:45:05,520
to find this.

379
00:45:07,440 --> 00:45:08,910
You want me to find this.

380
00:45:08,910 --> 00:45:13,220
No. You want you to find this.

381
00:45:13,220 --> 00:45:24,420
Because the finding of this, finds you incapacitorially finding and/or locating in your discovering the detecting of a way to save your dolly belle ol' what's her face.

382
00:45:24,420 --> 00:45:26,150
Savvy?

383
00:45:29,050 --> 00:45:30,900
This is going to save Elizabeth.

384
00:45:33,660 --> 00:45:36,190
How much do you know about Davy Jones?

385
00:45:38,560 --> 00:45:40,660
Not much.

386
00:45:40,660 --> 00:45:42,690
Yeah, it's going to save Elizabeth.

387
00:46:08,940 --> 00:46:10,650
What's all this?

388
00:46:12,210 --> 00:46:17,490
If you both fancy the dress, you'll just have to share and wear it one after the other.

389
00:46:17,490 --> 00:46:21,100
It's not like that, sir. This ship is haunted.

390
00:46:21,100 --> 00:46:23,830
Is it now?  You?

391
00:46:23,830 --> 00:46:27,490
There is a female presence amongst us here, sir.

392
00:46:27,490 --> 00:46:29,960
All the men, they can feel it.

393
00:46:29,960 --> 00:46:34,060
Belongs to a lady widowed before her marriage, I figure it.

394
00:46:34,060 --> 00:46:36,400
Searching for her husband lost the sea.

395
00:46:36,400 --> 00:46:41,250
Virgin, too, likely as not.  And that bodes ill by all accounts.

396
00:46:41,250 --> 00:46:45,670
I say that we throw the dress overboard and we hope the spirit follows it.

397
00:46:45,670 --> 00:46:48,610
No! That will just anger this spirit, sir.

398
00:46:48,610 --> 00:46:52,840
What we need to do is to find out what the spirit needs and then just get it back to her

399
00:46:52,840 --> 00:46:55,230
Enough! Enough!

400
00:46:55,230 --> 00:46:59,100
You're a pair of superstitious goats and it's got the best of ye.

401
00:46:59,100 --> 00:47:02,360
Now this appears to be as no more that we have a stowaway on board.

402
00:47:02,360 --> 00:47:07,460
A young woman, by the look of it. I want you to search the ship and find her.

403
00:47:07,460 --> 00:47:10,910
Oh, and, eh, she's probably naked.

404
00:47:39,690 --> 00:47:42,280
Why is Jack afraid of the open ocean?

405
00:47:42,280 --> 00:47:48,130
Well, if you believe such things, there's a beast does the bidding of Davy Jones.

406
00:47:48,130 --> 00:47:52,630
A fearsome creature with giant tentacles that suction your face clean off

407
00:47:52,630 --> 00:47:55,750
and drag an entire ship down to the crushing darkness.

408
00:47:57,900 --> 00:48:00,220
The Kraken.

409
00:48:02,090 --> 00:48:06,450
They say the stench of its breath is... ooh.

410
00:48:06,450 --> 00:48:17,560
Imagine, the last thing you know on God's green earth is the roar of the Kraken and the reeking odor of a thousand rotting corpses.

411
00:48:17,560 --> 00:48:20,440
If you believe such things.

412
00:48:20,440 --> 00:48:23,250
And the key will spare him that?

413
00:48:23,250 --> 00:48:26,130
Now that's the very question Jack wants answered.

414
00:48:26,130 --> 00:48:29,630
Bad enough even to go visit...

415
00:48:29,630 --> 00:48:31,850
her.

416
00:48:31,850 --> 00:48:33,760
Her?

417
00:48:33,760 --> 00:48:35,360
Aye.

418
00:49:09,880 --> 00:49:11,640
No worries, mates.

419
00:49:11,640 --> 00:49:14,750
Tia Dalma and I go way back. Thick as thieves.

420
00:49:14,750 --> 00:49:17,510
Nigh inseparable we are.

421
00:49:17,510 --> 00:49:22,260
Were... Have been. Before.

422
00:49:22,260 --> 00:49:23,410
I'll watch your back.

423
00:49:23,410 --> 00:49:24,820
It's me front I'm worried about.

424
00:49:24,820 --> 00:49:26,090
Mind the boat.

425
00:49:26,090 --> 00:49:26,780
Mind the boat.

426
00:49:27,990 --> 00:49:29,140
Mind the boat.

427
00:49:29,140 --> 00:49:29,530
Mind the boat.

428
00:49:30,650 --> 00:49:31,380
Mind the boat.

429
00:49:32,920 --> 00:49:37,110
Mind the boat.

430
00:49:47,400 --> 00:49:50,260
Jack Sparrow.

431
00:49:50,260 --> 00:49:51,450
Tia Dalma.

432
00:49:52,910 --> 00:49:57,970
I always knowed the wind was going to blow you back to me one day.

433
00:50:02,080 --> 00:50:06,360
You...

434
00:50:06,360 --> 00:50:12,430
You have a touch a' destiny about you.

435
00:50:12,430 --> 00:50:15,990
William. Turner.

436
00:50:15,990 --> 00:50:18,880
You know me?

437
00:50:18,880 --> 00:50:21,230
You want to know me.

438
00:50:21,230 --> 00:50:25,560
There'll be no knowing here.  We've come for help and we're not leaving without it.

439
00:50:25,560 --> 00:50:26,800
I thought I knew you.

440
00:50:26,800 --> 00:50:29,080
Not so well as I'd hoped. Come.

441
00:50:29,080 --> 00:50:31,660
Come.

442
00:50:35,880 --> 00:50:40,330
What service may I do ya?

443
00:50:40,330 --> 00:50:41,630
You know I demand payment.

444
00:50:41,630 --> 00:50:43,000
I brought payment.

445
00:50:50,290 --> 00:50:54,350
Look...  an undead monkey. Top that!

446
00:50:58,700 --> 00:51:03,520
No.  You've no idea how long it took us to catch that.

447
00:51:03,520 --> 00:51:05,910
The payment is fair.

448
00:51:05,910 --> 00:51:07,850
We're looking for this.

449
00:51:10,570 --> 00:51:12,180
And what it goes to.

450
00:51:14,670 --> 00:51:19,270
The compass you bartered from me, it cannot lead you to this?

451
00:51:19,270 --> 00:51:22,520
Maybe. Why?

452
00:51:24,950 --> 00:51:30,310
Jack Sparrow does not know what he wants.

453
00:51:30,310 --> 00:51:36,610
Or do you know but are loath to claim it as your own.

454
00:51:37,970 --> 00:51:45,250
Your key go to a chest. And it is what lay inside the chest you seek. Don't it?

455
00:51:45,250 --> 00:51:46,690
What is inside?

456
00:51:46,690 --> 00:51:52,460
Gold? Jewels? Unclaimed properties of valuable nature?

457
00:51:52,460 --> 00:51:56,280
Nothing bad, I hope.

458
00:51:56,280 --> 00:52:00,750
You know of Davy Jones, yes?

459
00:52:00,750 --> 00:52:03,360
A man of the sea.

460
00:52:03,360 --> 00:52:11,200
A great sailor. Until he run afoul of that which vex all men.

461
00:52:11,200 --> 00:52:15,400
What vexes all men?

462
00:52:15,400 --> 00:52:18,290
What indeed.

463
00:52:18,290 --> 00:52:19,240
The sea?

464
00:52:19,240 --> 00:52:20,640
Sums.

465
00:52:20,640 --> 00:52:23,870
The dichotomy of good and evil.

466
00:52:23,870 --> 00:52:26,080
A woman!

467
00:52:26,080 --> 00:52:29,870
A woman. He fell in love.

468
00:52:29,870 --> 00:52:33,040
No no no no, I heard it was the sea he fell in love with.

469
00:52:33,040 --> 00:52:36,630
Same story, different version and all are true.

470
00:52:36,630 --> 00:52:45,490
See it was a woman as changing, and harsh and untamable as the sea.

471
00:52:45,490 --> 00:52:47,800
He never stopped loving her.

472
00:52:47,800 --> 00:52:52,670
But the pain it caused him was too much to live with.

473
00:52:52,670 --> 00:52:57,300
But not enough to cause him to die.

474
00:52:57,300 --> 00:53:01,430
What exactly did he put into the chest?

475
00:53:01,430 --> 00:53:03,490
Him heart.

476
00:53:03,490 --> 00:53:05,680
Literally or figuratively?

477
00:53:05,680 --> 00:53:10,180
He couldn't live, putting his heart in a chest.

478
00:53:10,180 --> 00:53:12,430
Could he?

479
00:53:12,430 --> 00:53:20,050
It was not worth feeling what small, fleeting joy life brings. And so,

480
00:53:20,050 --> 00:53:29,020
him carved out him heart, lock it down in a chest, and hide the chest from the world.

481
00:53:29,020 --> 00:53:36,170
The key he keep with him at all times.

482
00:53:36,170 --> 00:53:37,280
You knew this.

483
00:53:37,280 --> 00:53:41,000
I did not. I didn't know where the key was. But now we do.

484
00:53:41,000 --> 00:53:47,050
So, all that's left is to climb aboard the Flying Dutchman, grab the key, you go back to Port Royal and save your bonnie lass, aye?

485
00:53:47,050 --> 00:53:49,430
Let me see your hand.

486
00:54:03,800 --> 00:54:07,980
The black spot! The black spot.

487
00:54:07,980 --> 00:54:10,470
Black spot.

488
00:54:10,470 --> 00:54:12,900
